      </a>
      <a class="ribbon-stage" href="#stage-5">
        <div class="ribbon-num">5</div>
        <div class="ribbon-label">Surveillance in flight</div>
        <div class="ribbon-substage">Trends, not appointments</div>
      </a>
      <a class="ribbon-stage" href="#stage-6">
        <div class="ribbon-num">6</div>
        <div class="ribbon-label">The clinic shape now</div>
        <div class="ribbon-substage">Time for the patients who need it</div>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- FRAMING -->
  <div class="framing">
    <div class="framing-grid">
      <div class="framing-tile">
        <div class="framing-tile-eyebrow">The clinical North Star</div>
        <div class="framing-tile-h">Clinical accountability preserved. Reach extended. Clinic time freed for the patients who need it.</div>
        <div class="framing-tile-body">Adam is not interested in a model that quietly removes him from the loop or sends raw numbers to patients without clinical interpretation. The result comes back to him first. He reads it against the PSA trajectory he is tracking. He decides what happens next. <strong>The model that earns clinician adoption is the one that protects clinical accountability rather than routing around it.</strong></div>
      </div>
      <div class="framing-tile">
        <div class="framing-tile-eyebrow">Why this works for him</div>
        <div class="framing-tile-h">Reach, adherence, capacity. Three clinical wins in the same move.</div>
        <div class="framing-tile-body"><strong>Reach.</strong> Patients the in-clinic service misses, rural travellers, shift workers, carers, the gradual drop-outs. <strong>Adherence.</strong> A kit at home does not get missed because of work, weather, transport or childcare. <strong>Capacity.</strong> Every routine quarterly monitoring done at home frees the slot for the patient who clinically needs the room. The pattern does not displace the clinical role. It changes which patients reach the clinic and why.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- STAGES -->
  <div class="stages">

    <!-- STAGE 1 -->
    <div class="stage" id="stage-1">
      <div class="stage-side">
        <div class="stage-number">01</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stage-main">
        <div class="stage-eyebrow">The cohort &middot; the patients in front of him</div>
        <h2 class="stage-title">Adam runs a PSA Active Surveillance clinic at a large acute trust. The cohort grows, the clinic doesn&apos;t. Some patients live far from the hospital, some work shifts, some care for someone at home. The drop-outs are the patients he worries about most. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="adam-s1"></span></h2>

        <div class="stage-image" style="padding:0;border:none;background:none;margin-bottom:22px;"><img src="Assets/Adam Story/adam-stage1.png" alt="Adam Stage 1" style="width:100%;height:auto;border-radius:12px;display:block;box-shadow:0 8px 24px rgba(0,32,64,0.12);"></div>

        <div class="pull-quote">
          <p class="pull-quote-text">I do not need a new tool. I need the patients I cannot see in clinic to stay in surveillance. Give me a reliable way to monitor them at home and put the result back in front of me, and I will use it.</p>
          <div class="pull-quote-attribution">Adam</div>
        </div>

        <div class="whats-happening">
          <div class="whats-happening-label">What he walks in with</div>
          <div class="whats-happening-body">A PSA Active Surveillance cohort growing year on year as more men are eligible. A quarterly clinic cycle. A list of patients who repeatedly miss appointments and a smaller list of patients who have stopped attending altogether. NICE NG131 surveillance guidance in his head. <strong>The clinical question is: how do I keep these men in surveillance without my clinic capacity being the limit?</strong></div>
        </div>

        <div class="old-way">
          <div class="old-way-label">The old way</div>
          <div class="old-way-body">Quarterly in-clinic phlebotomy and consultant review. The patient comes to the hospital, has a PSA drawn, and waits to be seen. The cohort that drops out is the cohort that loses surveillance. The clinical risk lands on the dropped patients, not on the model.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="careteam">
          <div class="careteam-icon">&#x1F465;</div>
          <div class="careteam-body">
            <div class="careteam-label">Who he is talking to</div>
            <div class="careteam-text">His clinical nurse specialist on the cohort. His MDT. His Trust&apos;s outpatient lead on capacity. The radiologist on the imaging follow-on. The patient.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="crosslinks">
          <div class="crosslinks-label">Where this lives in the model</div>
          <div class="crosslinks-row">
            <span class="crosslinks-tag">Who</span>
            <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Persona Adam.html" target="_blank">Adam persona</a>
            <span class="crosslinks-tag">Why</span>
            <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Why.html" target="_blank">Why this model</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- STAGE 2 -->
    <div class="stage" id="stage-2">
      <div class="stage-side">
        <div class="stage-number">02</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stage-main">
        <div class="stage-eyebrow">The drop-outs &middot; the clinic-only model&apos;s blind spot</div>
        <h2 class="stage-title">Follow-up appointments are fifty-four per cent of NHS outpatient activity. The PSA-AS quarterly review is exactly the kind of follow-up that never needed a room. The patients who drop out are the ones the clinic-only model was never going to hold. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="adam-s2"></span></h2>

        <div class="stage-image" style="padding:0;border:none;background:none;margin-bottom:22px;"><img src="Assets/Adam Story/adam-stage2.png" alt="Adam Stage 2" style="width:100%;height:auto;border-radius:12px;display:block;box-shadow:0 8px 24px rgba(0,32,64,0.12);"></div>

        <div class="pull-quote">
          <p class="pull-quote-text">The patients who miss the appointment are not refusing care. They are keeping their jobs, getting their kids to school, looking after a parent. The clinic was always the wrong venue for routine bloods. The risk was always in the model, not in them.</p>
          <div class="pull-quote-attribution">Adam</div>
        </div>

        <div class="whats-happening">
          <div class="whats-happening-label">What the data shows</div>
          <div class="whats-happening-body">Follow-up appointments account for around 54% of NHS outpatient activity. Eight million outpatient appointments went unattended in England in 2023/24. <strong>The PSA-AS quarterly review is precisely the kind of follow-up that, done remotely, releases clinic capacity for the patients who clinically need clinic time.</strong> Surveillance attrition is a known clinical problem in active surveillance cohorts.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="old-way">
          <div class="old-way-label">The clinic-only consequence</div>
          <div class="old-way-body">Patients who fall out of surveillance lose the safety net the surveillance provides. PSA trends are not detected. Disease progression is found later, sometimes too late. The clinical risk is invisible to the clinic and lands on the patient.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="careteam">
          <div class="careteam-icon">&#x1F465;</div>
          <div class="careteam-body">
            <div class="careteam-label">Who else sees this</div>
            <div class="careteam-text">Catherine, the Acute Trust commissioner who pays for the outpatient capacity Adam burns. The MDT colleagues with the same drop-out curve in their cohorts. The patient who stopped coming.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="crosslinks">
          <div class="crosslinks-label">Where this lives in the model</div>
          <div class="crosslinks-row">
            <span class="crosslinks-tag">Who</span>
            <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Persona Catherine.html" target="_blank">Catherine persona</a>
            <span class="crosslinks-tag">H&amp;M</span>
            <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Mark Journey.html" target="_blank">Mark&apos;s journey</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- STAGE 3 -->
    <div class="stage" id="stage-3">
      <div class="stage-side">
        <div class="stage-number">03</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stage-main">
        <div class="stage-eyebrow">The model&apos;s offer &middot; kit out, result back to him</div>
        <h2 class="stage-title">The home pathway sends the kit to the patient. The sample comes back to the lab. The PSA result lands on Adam&apos;s desk before the next clinic, in trend with everything that came before. The clinical role is preserved, the venue is not. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="adam-s3"></span></h2>

        <div class="stage-image" style="padding:0;border:none;background:none;margin-bottom:22px;"><img src="Assets/Adam Story/adam-stage3.png" alt="Adam Stage 3" style="width:100%;height:auto;border-radius:12px;display:block;box-shadow:0 8px 24px rgba(0,32,64,0.12);"></div>

        <div class="pull-quote">
          <p class="pull-quote-text">I am not interested in a model that sends raw numbers to a patient without clinical interpretation. I am interested in a model where the kit changes the venue and the clinical accountability does not move. That is what this is.</p>
          <div class="pull-quote-attribution">Adam</div>
        </div>

        <div class="whats-happening">
          <div class="whats-happening-label">What is preserved</div>
          <div class="whats-happening-body">The PSA result returns to Adam first, in trend, not to the patient as a raw number. The clinical review remains his. Threshold alerts (built on NICE NG131 surveillance guidance) escalate to him; routine in-range results are reviewed in the same MDT rhythm he uses now. <strong>The kit changes where the blood is drawn. It does not change who reads the trend.</strong></div>
        </div>

        <div class="old-way">
          <div class="old-way-label">What he was worried it would be</div>
          <div class="old-way-body">A model that bypasses the consultant, sends results direct to the patient, and removes the clinical interpretation step. Adam would not have adopted that. Most of his consultant colleagues would not have either. Clinician-initiated only works if the clinician&apos;s role is held.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="careteam">
          <div class="careteam-icon">&#x1F465;</div>
          <div class="careteam-body">
            <div class="careteam-label">Who governs the clinical pathway</div>
