        <div class="pull-quote">
          <p class="pull-quote-text">The silence is doing clinical work. Every result is reviewed in trend, and escalation happens when the line moves. Safety is the review, not the appointment. That is what surveillance was supposed to be all along.</p>
          <div class="pull-quote-attribution">Adam</div>
        </div>

        <div class="whats-happening">
          <div class="whats-happening-label">How surveillance actually works now</div>
          <div class="whats-happening-body">Routine in-range PSA results are reviewed in trend by Adam in the same MDT rhythm. Threshold breaches (rate of change, absolute value) trigger an alert and an MDT discussion within a defined window. Patients who would benefit from clinic are seen in clinic. Patients whose disease is stable stay home for the next quarterly cycle. <strong>The model surfaces clinical signal, not appointment volume.</strong></div>
        </div>

        <div class="old-way">
          <div class="old-way-label">The old rhythm</div>
          <div class="old-way-body">Every quarter, every patient, in clinic regardless of trend. The signal-to-noise ratio of in-clinic surveillance was poor because most appointments confirmed stability rather than detecting change. The clinically interesting patients shared clinic time with the clinically uneventful ones.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="careteam">
          <div class="careteam-icon">&#x1F465;</div>
          <div class="careteam-body">
            <div class="careteam-label">Who is in the loop</div>
            <div class="careteam-text">The MDT, holding the trend review. The CNS, coordinating between routine surveillance and escalation. Priya on the data layer, ensuring the result writes back to the Trust EPR cleanly. The patient, getting on with their life between cycles.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

